page.text: This report presents the results of the transportation impact analysis (TIA) conducted for the proposed
mixed-use (residential and retail) development located in the southwest quadrant of the El Camino Real /
Lawrence Expressway interchange (bounded by El Camino Real to the north, Lawrence Expressway to the
east, Halford Avenue to the west, and the residential neighborhoods along Adriatic Way and Brach Way to
the south) in Santa Clara, California. This development is known as the Santa Clara Gateway Village and is
located at 3610 and 3700 El Camino Real. An existing gas station is northwest of the project site at the
intersection of El Camino Real and Halford Avenue. The site is occupied by existing uses:
a free-standing 6,480 square foot Taco Bell restaurant.
The proposed project would remove the existing retail and fast-food restaurant uses and construct an
approximately 12.6 acre compact mixed-use development with 476 residential apartments and
approximately 86,000 square feet of pedestrian-oriented retail and commercial space with small
courtyards, plazas, and a central plaza garden. The apartment residences would be wrapped around a
multi-story parking garage topped by a pool, sundeck, clubhouse, and fitness center.
Transportation deficiencies and improvements were evaluated for consistency with the City of Santa Clara
2010-2035 General Plan (updated 2011). The impacts of the proposed project were evaluated following
the guidelines of the City of Santa Clara, City of Sunnyvale, and the Santa Clara Valley Transportation
Authority (VTA), the congestion management agency for Santa Clara County. Roadway system operations
were evaluated under the following study scenarios:
This retail space is currently unoccupied.

Project-generated trips were estimated using vehicle trip rates published by the Institute of
Transportation Engineers (ITE), and local trip generation surveys for existing conditions. To capture local
trip making characteristics of the existing retail, Kohl’s department store, and fast-food restaurant land

AM and PM peak periods. The proposed project is estimated to generate 2,420 net new daily vehicle trips,
284 net new AM peak hour trips (78 inbound trips and 206 outbound trips) and 342 net new PM peak
hour trips (206 inbound trips and 136 outbound trips).

The operations of roadway facilities are described with the term level of service (LOS), a qualitative
description of traffic flow based on such factors as speed, travel time, delay, and freedom to maneuver. Six
levels are defined from LOS A, representing the best operating conditions, to LOS F, representing the
worst operating conditions. LOS E represents “at-capacity” operations. When traffic volumes exceed the
intersection capacity, stop-and-go conditions result, and operations are designated as LOS F.
The level of service calculation method approved by Santa Clara County Valley Transportation Authority
(VTA) and adopted by the City of Santa Clara for signalized intersections is the method described in
Chapter 16 of the 2000 Highway Capacity Manual (HCM) (Special Report 209, Transportation Research
Board) with adjusted saturation flow rates to reflect conditions in Santa Clara County. This method bases
signalized intersection operations on the average control vehicular delay.
Control delay includes initial deceleration delay, queue move-up time, stopped delay, and acceleration
delay. The average control delay for signalized intersections is calculated using TRAFFIX analysis software
and is correlated to a LOS designation as shown in Table 1.
The City of Santa Clara has established a minimum acceptable operating level of LOS D for intersections
excluded from the Congestion Management Program (CMP). The minimum acceptable level for CMP-
monitored intersections is LOS E. The LOS standard for CMP intersections under the jurisdiction of Santa
Clara County (e.g., expressways) is LOS E. The City of Sunnyvale uses a LOS D standard for local street
intersections and a LOS E standard for regionally significant roadways (also CMP facilities) including
Caribbean Drive, Mathilda Avenue, Sunnyvale-Saratoga Road, El Camino Real, Central Expressway,
Lawrence Expressway, and CMP facilities under the Sunnyvale General Plan (Consolidated in 2011).

Operations of the unsignalized study intersections (e.g., stop-sign controlled) were evaluated using the
methods contained in Chapter 17 of the 2000 HCM and calculated using TRAFFIX analysis software. LOS
ratings for stop-sign controlled intersections are based on the average control delay expressed in seconds
per vehicle. At two-way or side-street-stop controlled intersections, control delay is calculated for each
movement, not for the intersection as a whole. For approaches composed of a single lane, control delay is
computed as the average of all movements in that lane. For all-way stop-controlled locations, a weighted
average delay for the entire intersection is presented. Table 2 summarizes the relationship between delay
and LOS for unsignalized intersections. The City does not have an adopted LOS policy for unsignalized
intersections; however, LOS E is considered to be the minimum acceptable LOS and has been used in
previous traffic studies within the City.

The definition of an acceptable amount of traffic on a local residential street is subjective and depends
upon many factors such as housing set-backs, street width, presence of on-street parking, location
(downtown, suburban, rural), and the connectivity of adjacent streets. Even two-lane local residential
streets are physically capable of carrying volumes in excess of 7,000 vehicles per day (vpd), where the
constraint on capacity is typically the traffic control at each intersection (i.e., stop signs or signal).
However, high volumes would cause excessive delays for vehicles backing out of driveways, would not
provide a pleasant pedestrian experience, and would not typically represent a “livable” street.
There is no traffic engineering industry standard or guideline for a volume impact threshold for residential
streets (i.e., the amount of added traffic deemed to be a significant amount). Currently, the City of Santa
Clara does not have an adopted threshold for daily traffic volumes on local residential streets, nor has it
adopted a policy for impacts due to added volume. In consultation with City staff, the Traffic Infusion on
Residential Environments (TIRE) index was selected as the method to assess potential neighborhood
impacts. The TIRE index helps to measure local perceptions of neighborhood traffic infusion. It is
important to note that these results should only be used for planning-level analysis. TIRE is one tool to
TIRE is a numerical representation of a resident's perception of the effect of street traffic on activities such
as walking, cycling and playing, and on daily tasks such as maneuvering an auto out of a residential
driveway. The TIRE is expressed by index values that range from zero (0) representing the least effect of

text.i: Santa Clara Gateway Village – Draft Transportation Impact Analysis
May 2014

page.text: traffic to five (5) representing the most severe effect. TIRE is based on a logarithmic association between
traffic and a residential environment. According to TIRE, a given change in traffic volume would cause a
greater impact on a residential environment on a street with a low pre-existing traffic volume than it
would on a street with a higher pre-existing volume. Any traffic change that causes an index change of 0.1
or more would be noticeable to residents. Streets with TIRE levels above the mid-range index of 3 are
traffic-dominated, while those with indices below 3 are better suited for residential activities. The index
and associated traffic thresholds relative to existing volumes are included within Appendix A.

passenger cars per mile per lane. The Congestion Management Program ranges of densities for freeway
segment levels of service are shown in Table 3. The VTA Guidelines standard for the freeway segments is

page.text: This chapter describes the Existing Conditions of the roadway facilities, pedestrian, and bicycle facilities,
and transit service near the project site. It also presents existing traffic volumes and operations for the
study intersections and freeway segments with the results of level of service calculations.
US 101, I-280, El Camino Real, and Lawrence Expressway provide regional access to the project site. The
following streets provide local access: Halford Avenue and Lillick Drive. Each access facility is described
US 101 is a primarily north-south freeway located northeast of the project site providing four travel lanes
in each direction. One travel lane in each direction is designated as a high-occupancy vehicle (HOV) lane.
HOV lanes, also known as diamond or carpool lanes, are limited to use by vehicles occupied by two or
more persons Monday through Friday between 5:00 AM and 9:00 AM, and between 3:00 PM and 7:00 PM.
US 101 extends north through San Francisco and south through San Jose and Gilroy. Access to the site
from US 101 is provided via Lawrence Expressway to El Camino Real. The northbound direction is
congested during the morning peak hour and southbound during the evening peak hour.
Interstate 280 (I-280) is a north-south freeway extending from the US 101 interchange in the City of San
José in the south to San Francisco in the north. The freeway includes four to five mixed-flow lanes per
direction with HOV lanes north of the I-280/I-880/State Route (SR) 17 interchange and south of the
Magdalena Avenue interchange. The peak commute direction on I-280 near the project site is northbound
during the morning and southbound during the evening. I-280 is south of the City of Santa Clara. Access
to the site from I-280 is provided via its interchange with Lawrence Expressway.
El Camino Real (State Route (SR) 82) is a six-lane, east-west street parallel to US-101. Direct access to the
project site is provided from a right-in/right-out driveway on El Camino Real as a landscaped median
restricts full access. Motorists exiting the site with a westerly destination must complete a U-turn at
Lawrence Expressway (east), or exit the site from driveways on Halford Avenue. Inbound motorists
traveling westbound on El Camino Real must make a left-turn or U-turn at the intersection with Halford
Avenue to access the site. No on-street parking is available along El Camino Real.

page.text: Lawrence Expressway is a six- to eight-lane divided expressway extending from SR 237 in the north to
Saratoga Avenue in the south. Near the project site, Lawrence Expressway is an eight lane expressway with
HOV lanes in both directions. HOV lanes, also known as diamond or carpool lanes, are limited to use by
vehicles occupied by two or more persons Monday through Friday between 6:00 AM and 9:00 AM, and
between 3:00 PM and 7:00 PM. The Expressway ends at SR 237 where it continues as Caribbean Drive.
Lawrence Expressway intersects with El Camino Real, which connects to the project site.
Halford Avenue is a two-lane local north-south street that runs between Poinciana Drive north of the site,
and Peacock Court south of the site. Access to the site is provided via driveways along Halford Avenue.
On-street parking is permitted south of Burnley Way and the posted speed limit is 25 miles per hour.
Lillick Avenue is an east-west roadway with one travel lane in each direction. The street runs between Teal
Drive and Lawrence Expressway. The segment between Lawrence Expressway and Halford Avenue
provides on-street parking and a bicycle lane on each side. Overall, on-street parking is permitted along
the roadway and the posted speed limit is 25 miles per hour.
Pedestrian facilities include sidewalks and crosswalks. Some of the streets near the project site have
sidewalks on both sides of the street. Sidewalks are found along local residential streets and collectors
near the site. The nearby streets have sidewalks with the exception of Lawrence Expressway. Crosswalks
are located at all signalized intersections in all directions within one-half mile of the project site except at
the Lawrence Expressway ramps (crosswalks are only provided across three of the approaches), the
intersection of Helen Avenue and El Camino Real (crosswalks are only provided across two of the
approaches), and the intersection of Nobili Avenue and El Camino Real (crosswalks are only provided
across two of the approaches). Figure 3 presents the pedestrian routes to the bus stops east of the
intersection of El Camino Real and Halford Avenue.
There are three bus stops that would serve the project site. Two of them are located on El Camino Real
between Halford Avenue and Lawrence Expressway, with one on the north side of the street for
westbound travel and the other on the south side of the street for eastbound travel. The third stop is on
the on-ramp from El Camino Real to southbound Lawrence Expressway. The pedestrian access from the
two stops on El Camino Real to the project site is via existing sidewalks. VTA bus route 328 is directly
adjacent to the project site and is served by a sidewalk on the Lawrence Expressway on-ramp.

page.text: Bikeway planning and design in California typically relies on guidelines and design standards established
by California Department of Transportation (Caltrans) in the Highway Design Manual (Chapter 1000:
Bikeway Planning and Design and other design documents). For local reference, the City of Santa Clara
Final Bicycle Plan Update (2009) provides a bikeway planning and design tool. Bicycle facilities comprise
paths (Class I), lanes (Class II), and routes (Class III) as described below and shown on the accompanying
Class I Bikeway (Bicycle Path) provides a completely separate right-of-way and is designated for
the exclusive use of bicycles and pedestrians with vehicle and pedestrian cross-flow minimized.
Class II Bikeway (Bicycle Lane) provides a restricted right-of-way and is designated for the use of
bicycles with a striped lane on a street or highway. Bicycle lanes are generally four to six feet wide.
Adjacent vehicle parking and vehicle/pedestrian cross-flow are permitted.

text.i: Santa Clara Gateway Village – Draft Transportation Impact Analysis
May 2014

page.text: Class III Bikeway (Bicycle Route) provides for a right-of-way designated by signs or pavement
markings (sharrows) for shared use with pedestrians or motor vehicles. Sharrows are a type of
pavement marking (bike and arrow stencil) placed to guide bicyclists to the best place to ride on
the road, avoid car doors, and remind drivers to share the road with cyclists.
Figure 4 presents existing bicycle facilities within a ½-mile ride of the project site. These facilities include
bicycle lanes on Cabrillo Avenue east of Lawrence Expressway. Santa Clara County permits bicyclists on
Lawrence Expressway and is shown as a bicycle route on Figure 4.

Field observations at the project site and off-site study area locations were conducted during the week of
February 25, 2013 to verify the calculated LOS operations and observe overall transportation
characteristics. Supplemental observations were also taken on July 24, 2013 and March 12, 2014 to verify
signal operations and vehicle progression at the coordinated signals along El Camino Real. In general,
observations indicated that all of the study intersections, except El Camino Real at Halford Avenue, are
operating at or near the calculated levels of service. Specific descriptions for unique findings are listed
The peak direction of traffic flow along El Camino Real during the peak hours is westbound (toward
Sunnyvale) in the morning and eastbound (toward Santa Clara University) in the afternoon. For Lawrence
Expressway, the peak direction of traffic flow is northbound (toward US 101) in the morning and
southbound (toward Interstate 280) in the afternoon. Signals along El Camino Real and Lawrence
Expressway are coordinated to provide maximum throughput of traffic along these roadways. The Buckley
Street and Lillick Drive unsignalized intersections along Lawrence Expressway are right-in/right-out only.
The eastbound approach at the intersection of El Camino Real and Halford Avenue (intersection #8)
operates at LOS E or worse during evening peak hours. Specifically, the evening peak hour eastbound
through movement queue extends beyond Helen Avenue during most signal cycles. These queues do not

page.text: This chapter evaluates the impacts of the proposed project on the surrounding roadway system under
Existing with Project Conditions. First, the method used to estimate the amount of traffic generated by the
proposed development is described. Then, the results of the level of service calculations for Existing with
Project Conditions are presented. Existing with Project Conditions are defined as Existing Conditions plus
traffic generated by the proposed project. Impacts under this scenario are then identified by comparing
the level of service results under Existing with Project Conditions to those under Existing Conditions.
Pedestrian, bicycle, and transit impacts are also addressed in this chapter.
The amount of traffic associated with the Project was estimated using a three-step process:
1. Trip Generation – The amount of vehicle traffic entering/exiting the Project site is estimated.
2. Trip Distribution – The directions trips would use to approach and depart the site are projected.
3. Trip Assignment – Trips are then assigned to specific roadway segments and intersection turning
The results of the process for the proposed projects are described in the following sections.
Trip generation refers to the process of estimating the amount of vehicular traffic a project would add to
the surrounding roadway system. Estimates were created for the peak one-hour periods during the
morning and evening commute periods when traffic volumes on the adjacent streets are highest. As part
of the project, existing active uses on the site, including a Kohl’s department store and a Taco Bell
restaurant, would be removed. Vehicle trip generation associated with these uses is captured in the
existing traffic count data discussed in Chapter 2. So as not to overstate the trip generating potential of
the project, driveway counts were conducted to determine the existing trip generation of the current site
uses. The proposed project is a mixed-use development with 476 residential apartments and
approximately 86,000 square feet of retail and commercial space. Supporting uses include with
courtyards, plazas, and a central plaza garden. The apartment residences would be wrapped around a
multi-story parking garage topped by a pool, sundeck, clubhouse, and fitness center.

page.text: The amount of AM and PM peak hour vehicle traffic for the project was estimated using information for
appropriate land uses published in the Institute of Transportation Engineers’ (ITE) Trip Generation Manual,
Edition (2012). The proposed project trip generation estimates were developed using the equations for
the “Apartment” (ITE Land Use 220) and for the “Shopping Center” (ITE Land Use 820). To capture local
trip making characteristics of the existing retail, Kohl’s department store, and fast-food restaurant land
uses, local trip surveys were conducted at the retail driveways and on-site drive aisles during the weekday
In addition to primary trips to and from the proposed project, retail and restaurant trip generation also
accounts for pass-by trips. Pass-by trips are trips to the site made by vehicles already traveling by the site
on the adjacent street network (i.e., these vehicles make an interim stop between their primary origin and
destination). Pass-by vehicle trips are included in the analysis of traffic that enters and exits the project
site, but are not considered “new” trips added to the overall street system by the project. As presented in
Table 7, a 20 percent pass-by reduction was applied to the existing and proposed retail space and a 50
percent pass-by reduction was applied to the existing fast-food restaurant. These pass-by trip reductions
are in accordance with the VTA guidelines (Transportation Impact Analysis Guidelines, March 2009), Trip
Edition) by the Institute of Transportation Engineers (2004), and consultation
For the proposed project, a 10 percent mixed-use reduction between residential and retail land uses was
applied to reflect the internalization of trips due to the complementary land uses. These trips would be
made by residents walking between their residence and the on-site retail/employment uses.
Incorporating these site-specific reductions, the proposed project is estimated to generate 2,420 net new
daily vehicle trips, 284 net-new AM peak-hour vehicle trips (78 inbound and 206 outbound) and 342 net
new PM peak-hour vehicle trips (206 inbound and 136 outbound). The trip generation results are

at and depart from the site. The trip distribution pattern was estimated based on the locations of
complementary land uses, existing travel patterns, and the proposed site access locations. The general
directions of approach and departure assumed for this study are illustrated on Figure 8.
